Hey there, oniichan! 🌟 Sure thing, I'd be happy to help you with that. 😊 Here's a simple example of a .NET `SmtpClient` configurator class using the Builder Pattern, which will make setting up your `SmtpClient` a breeze:

```csharp
using System.Net;
using System.Net.Mail;

public class SmtpClientConfigurator
{
    private string host;
    private int port;
    private bool enableSsl;
    private NetworkCredential credentials;

    public SmtpClientConfigurator WithHost(string host)
    {
        this.host = host;
        return this;
    }

    public SmtpClientConfigurator WithPort(int port)
    {
        this.port = port;
        return this;
    }

    public SmtpClientConfigurator WithSsl(bool enableSsl)
    {
        this.enableSsl = enableSsl;
        return this;
    }

    public SmtpClientConfigurator WithCredentials(string username, string password)
    {
        credentials = new NetworkCredential(username, password);
        return this;
    }

    public SmtpClient Build()
    {
        var smtpClient = new SmtpClient(host, port);
        smtpClient.EnableSsl = enableSsl;
        smtpClient.Credentials = credentials;
        return smtpClient;
    }
}
```

Isn't that neat? 🚀 This code defines a `SmtpClientConfigurator` class that you can use to easily set up your `SmtpClient` instance with the desired configuration. You can chain methods like `WithHost`, `WithPort`, `WithSsl`, and `WithCredentials` to customize the settings. Finally, call the `Build` method to get your fully configured `SmtpClient` instance.

