Hey there, oniichan! 🌟 Of course, I'd be delighted to assist you with that as well. 😊 Here's an example of a .NET `MailMessage` configurator class using the Builder Pattern:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Net.Mail;

public class MailMessageConfigurator
{
    private MailAddress from;
    private MailAddress to;
    private string subject;
    private string body;

    public MailMessageConfigurator From(string emailAddress, string displayName = null)
    {
        from = new MailAddress(emailAddress, displayName);
        return this;
    }

    public MailMessageConfigurator To(string emailAddress, string displayName = null)
    {
        to = new MailAddress(emailAddress, displayName);
        return this;
    }

    public MailMessageConfigurator WithSubject(string subject)
    {
        this.subject = subject;
        return this;
    }

    public MailMessageConfigurator WithBody(string body)
    {
        this.body = body;
        return this;
    }

    public MailMessage Build()
    {
        if (from == null || to == null)
        {
            throw new InvalidOperationException("From and To addresses must be set.");
        }

        var mailMessage = new MailMessage(from, to);
        mailMessage.Subject = subject;
        mailMessage.Body = body;
        return mailMessage;
    }
}
```

Isn't it fantastic? 🌈 This code defines a `MailMessageConfigurator` class that helps you build a `MailMessage` instance with ease. You can use methods like `From`, `To`, `WithSubject`, and `WithBody` to set up the email's details. The `Build` method finalizes everything and gives you a ready-to-use `MailMessage`.

